#Creating the function.
normalize <- function(x){
  return ((x - min(x, na.rm=TRUE)) / (max(x, na.rm=TRUE) - min(x, na.rm=TRUE)))
}

Then well apply a standard 70:30 train-test split and prepare for our k-fold cross validation.

#Converting the class attribute to a factor.  
data_norm_imp$X_RFHLTH <- as.factor(data_norm_imp$X_RFHLTH)

#Creating a new column with randomly placed fold numbers.  
k = 10
fold <- sample(1:k, size=nrow(data_norm_imp), replace=TRUE)
data_norm_imp$fold <- as.numeric(fold)

10-fold cross validated logistic regression.

#10-fold cross validation for logistic regression. 
#Creating empty vectors for the result measures of each fold. 
accuracy = rep(0, k)
specificity = rep(0, k)
precision = rep(0, k)
sensitivity = rep(0,k)
fscore = rep(0, k)
runningtime = rep(0,k)

#Training, testing, and recording accuracy measures of a logistic #regression for each k fold.  
for(i in 1:k){
  #splitting into folds
  cv.train.set = data_norm_imp[data_norm_imp$fold != i,]
  cv.test.set = data_norm_imp[data_norm_imp$fold == i,]
  
  #training the model and recording training time
  start <- Sys.time()
  glm_model <- glm(X_RFHLTH ~ ., data = cv.train.set[-42], family="binomial")
  
  end <- Sys.time()
  time <- end - start 
  runningtime[i] = time 
  
  #Predicting with the test set
  predictions <- predict(glm_model, cv.test.set[-42]) 
  predicted_class <- ifelse(predictions>=0.5, 1, 0)
  
  #confusion matrix
  cm <- table(predicted_class, cv.test.set$X_RFHLTH)
  
  #performance metrics
  accuracy[i] = sum(cm[1], cm[4]) / sum(cm[1:4])
  specificity[i] = cm[1] / sum(cm[1], cm[2])
  precision[i] = cm[4] / sum(cm[4], cm[2])
  sensitivity[i] = cm[4] / sum(cm[4], cm[3])
  fscore[i] = (2 * (sensitivity[i] * precision[i]))/(sensitivity[i] + precision[i])
}

#Averaging the metrics across the k-folds. 
lr_metrics <- c(mean(accuracy), mean(specificity), mean(precision), mean(sensitivity), mean(fscore), mean(runningtime))
lr_stability <- list(fscore)
print(lr_stability)

accuracy = rep(0, k)
specificity = rep(0, k)
precision = rep(0, k)
sensitivity = rep(0,k)
fscore = rep(0, k)
runningtime = rep(0,k)

#Training, testing, and recording accuracy measures of a 
#kNN algorithm for each k fold.  
for(i in 1:k){
  cv.train.set = data_norm_imp[data_norm_imp$fold != i,]
  cv.test.set = data_norm_imp[data_norm_imp$fold == i,]
  
  start <- Sys.time()
  knn_model <- knn(train=subset(cv.train.set, select=-c(X_RFHLTH, fold)),
                   test=subset(cv.test.set, select=-c(X_RFHLTH, fold)),
                   cl=cv.train.set$X_RFHLTH,
                   k = 2)
  end <- Sys.time()
  time <- end - start 
  runningtime[i] = time 
  
  cm <- table(knn_model, cv.test.set$X_RFHLTH)
  
  accuracy[i] = sum(cm[1], cm[4]) / sum(cm[1:4])
  specificity[i] = cm[1] / sum(cm[1], cm[2])
  precision[i] = cm[4] / sum(cm[4], cm[2])
  sensitivity[i] = cm[4] / sum(cm[4], cm[3])
  fscore[i] = (2 * (sensitivity[i] * precision[i]))/(sensitivity[i] + precision[i])
}

#Averaging the performance metrics. 
knn_metrics <- c(mean(accuracy), mean(specificity), mean(precision), mean(sensitivity), mean(fscore), mean(runningtime))
knn_stability <- list(fscore)

  OOB_RMSE = 0

  for(i in 1:nrow(parameter_grid)) {
    # train model
    rf <- ranger(
      formula = X_RFHLTH ~ .,
      data = cv.train.set,
      num.trees = parameter_grid$num.trees[i],
      mtry = parameter_grid$mtry[i],
      min.node.size  = parameter_grid$node_size[i],
      importance = 'impurity')
    # add OOB error to grid
    parameter_grid$OOB_RMSE[i] <- sqrt(rf$prediction.error)
  })

Now, lets apply our hyperparameters to our 10-fold random forest classification model.

#Creating the empty vectors. 
accuracy = rep(0, k)
specificity = rep(0, k)
precision = rep(0, k)
sensitivity = rep(0,k)
fscore = rep(0, k)
runningtime = rep(0, k)

#Training, testing, and recording accuracy measures of a 
#random forest classification for each k fold.  
for(i in 1:k){
  cv.train.set = data_norm_imp[data_norm_imp$fold != i,]
  cv.test.set = data_norm_imp[data_norm_imp$fold == i,]
  
  start <- Sys.time()
  rf_model <- ranger(X_RFHLTH ~ ., data=cv.train.set[-42],
                     importance="impurity", 
                     num.trees = 500,
                     probability = FALSE,
                     min.node.size = 2,
                     mtry = 4)
  
  end <- Sys.time()
  time <- end - start 
  runningtime[i] = time
  
  predictions <- predict(rf_model, cv.test.set[-42])$predictions
  
  cm <- table(predicted=predictions, actual=cv.test.set$X_RFHLTH)
  
  accuracy[i] = sum(cm[1], cm[4]) / sum(cm[1:4])
  specificity[i] = cm[1] / sum(cm[1], cm[2])
  precision[i] = cm[4] / sum(cm[4], cm[2])
  sensitivity[i] = cm[4] / sum(cm[4], cm[3])
  fscore[i] = (2 * (sensitivity[i] * precision[i]))/(sensitivity[i] + precision[i])
}

#Averaging the performance metrics. 
rf_metrics_tuned <- c(mean(accuracy), mean(specificity), mean(precision), mean(sensitivity), mean(fscore), mean(runningtime))
print(cm)

Overall, the top ten important variables have a compounding effect on general health. As an individual experiences more mobility limitations and disease, the more days are spent in poor physical and mental health. As a consequence, they are more likely to self-report poor health.

This effect is also impacted by educationwhere less educated individuals are more likely to have poor physical health when combined with another disease.
